= Politics Turns Demand Into Decisions

The public creates demand by raising concerns, voting, attending meetings, sharing complaints, asking for services, and organizing around needs.

Government manages that demand through politics.

Politics is not only elections. It is also:

- Public meetings
- Committee discussions
- Department updates
- Strategic plans
- Budget hearings
- City commission votes
- Board decisions
- Grant applications
- Program approvals

#compact-flow("How Demand Becomes Action", (
  ("Public Demand", "Meeting Discussion", "Vote or Priority"),
  ("Department Assignment", "Program or Project", "Funding Path"),
  ("RFP or Grant", "Organization Does Work"),
))

Departments manage the energy of public demand. Agencies, nonprofits, schools, and companies help make the work happen.

= Federal Departments Manage Big Problems

Federal departments are not just names to memorize. Each department manages a category of public problems.

#pro-table((1.1fr, 1.4fr), (
  [#text(fill: white)[Federal Department]], [#text(fill: white)[Problem Managed]],
  [Department of Education], [Student outcomes, college access, school support],
  [Department of Labor], [Jobs, training, workforce pathways],
  [HUD], [Housing, neighborhoods, community development],
  [HHS], [Health, families, human services],
  [Department of Transportation], [Mobility, roads, transit, infrastructure],
  [Department of Energy], [Energy, utilities, efficiency, resilience],
  [USDA], [Food, rural development, agriculture, nutrition],
  [Department of Commerce], [Economic growth, business development, industry],
))

Every local department has a relationship to bigger systems above it. A city workforce office may connect to state workforce funding. A housing department may connect to HUD. A transportation project may connect to federal infrastructure dollars.

#callout("What to look for")[
  Do not stop at “this department has a budget.” Ask: What larger federal or state priority is this connected to?
]

= GVSU TRIO Upward Bound Example

GVSU TRIO Upward Bound is a strong example because it shows how federal money can become a local program students can actually touch.

